This paper is about non-autoregressive neural machine translation, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes an imitation learning framework, which involves training a model to imitate the behavior of an expert, and this falls under the category of machine learning (ML). Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses neural networks for translation, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of attention mechanisms, which are commonly used in neural networks for NLP tasks, and this falls under the category of neural networks (NE), making cs.NE another likely sub-category. Finally, the paper uses datasets that involve text and speech, which falls under the category of computer vision and pattern recognition (CV), making cs.CV a less likely but still possible sub-category.
